 England":"Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sulham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the three places called Pulham, in Norfolk, Dorset, and Devon. The placenames derive from Old English <i>pōl, pull</i> ‘pool’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’ or <i>hamm</i> ‘water meadow’."],"variants":[{"name":"Poland","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Hampshire called Poland, which probably derives from Old English <i>Pōling</i> or <i>Pulling</i> ‘pool place’. Alternatively, it may be a variant of any of the similar (like-sounding) English surnames, such as   Pulham   and   Pullen  , altered by folk etymology to conform to the name of the country in central Europe.","Irish (County Offaly, also Armagh and Down): variant of   Polin  . Compare   Polan  .","German: ethnic name from Middle High German <i>Polan</i> ‘Poland’ + excrescent <i>-d</i>, denoting an ethnic Pole or someone with Polish connections."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William de Sulham was born about 1200, in Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Aimery de Sulham, was 22 and his mother, Unknown, was 30. He had at least 1 daughter with Sara Unknown. He died about 1250, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1200–about 1250":"umbes 1200–umbes 1250","1200–1250":"1200–1250","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1180–1211":"1180–1211","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1205":"1205","1235":"1235","1211":"1211","1200":"1200","about 1200":"umbes 1200","about 1299":"umbes 1299","1250":"1250","1172":"1172","after 1211":"pärast 1211","1180":"1180","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sulham, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1200–about 1250":"noin 1200–noin 1250","1200–1250":"1200–1250","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","1180–1211":"1180–1211","1172–Female":"1172–Kuollut","about 1250":"noin 1250","1205":"1205","1235":"1235","1211":"1211","1200":"1200","about 1200":"noin 1200","about 1299":"noin 1299","1250":"1250","1172":"1172","after 1211":"1211 jälkeen","1180":"1180","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sulham, Berkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuni